":{"1107–1168":"1107–1168","1103–1149":"1103–1149","1134–1198":"1134–1198","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1168":"1168","1134":"1134","1133":"1133","1198":"1198","about 1134":"about 1134","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Bridlington, Yorkshire, England":"Bridlington, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scrope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: of uncertain origin. Tengvik suggests derivation from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Skrópi</i> (of doubtful etymology, but compare Old Scandinavian  <i>skrópa-maðr</i> ‘hypocrite’, containing the genitive plural form of  <i>skrópar</i> ‘sham, hypocrisy’). It is possible, but not certain, that this personal name forms the first element of the Notts place-name Scrooby. Otherwise there is no evidence for its currency in England or, more relevantly, in Normandy. Richards Castle (in Herefs and Shrops) was apparently named after Richard Scrope, who held estates in Herefs and Worcs in 1066 and was a Norman favourite of Edward the Confessor. The Scrope family, whose name is traditionally pronounced /skru:p/, was politically important in medieval England, and acquired estates in Lincs (Barton on Humber), NR Yorks (Castle Bolton), and in ER Yorks (Flotmanby). Richard (le) Scrope of Bolton, in Wensleydale, was Lord Chancellor in the reign of Richard II. The use of  <i>le</i> and  <i>de</i> in the surname, suggesting either a nickname or a locative name, must be treated with caution because these were often added gratuitously to Anglo-Norman surnames as a sign of high social status."],"variants":[{"name":"Scroop","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]},{"name":"Scroope","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Scrope was born in 1107, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh I SCROPE in 1133, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1168, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1107–1168":"1107–1168","1103–1149":"1103–1149","1134–1198":"1134–1198","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1168":"1168","1134":"1134","1133":"1133","1198":"1198","about 1134":"umbes 1134","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bridlington, Yorkshire, England":"Bridlington, Yorkshire, England","Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1107–1168":"1107–1168","1103–1149":"1103–1149","1134–1198":"1134–1198","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1103":"1103","1168":"1168","1134":"1134","1133":"1133","1198":"1198","about 1134":"noin 1134","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bridlington, Yorkshire, England":"Bridlington, Yorkshire